Washington, D.C.; About Narrator: No info provided.; Collection:U004 BASEMENT Room 024: Southwest Oral Histor ; Notes:Cal Thomas interviews Senator Campbell and addresses questions on terrorism, amendments to bills, death penalty, Bosnian conflict, environmental issues, switching to republican party, and gambling.;

Indians of North America--Anecdotes--1996
Legislators--United States--1996
Washington, D.C.; About Narrator: No info provided.; Collection:U004 BASEMENT Room 024: Southwest Oral Histor ; Notes:Topics covered are Indian veterans and Congressional Native involvement, or the lack of it. Talks specifically about the issues Native American veterans have accessing veteran's benefits that clash with trust status and life on reservations. Also talks about changes in how tribes communicate and interact with the federal government, direct contact between tribal leaders and the government instead of through non-native legal representatives as intermediaries. ;

Indians of North America--Anecdotes--1988
Jewelry making--Colorado--Ignacio--1988
Denver (Colo.)--History; About Narrator: No info provided.; Collection:U004 BASEMENT Room 024: Southwest Oral Histor ; Notes:Footage of the 7th annual Indian Market in Denver. Includes a short interview with Ben Nighthorse Campbell regarding his jewelry making, thoughts on politics. Mentions creation of a Dinosaur National Park. Other footage is of artisans and Native dances.;

Arts--Censorship--United States
Legislators--United States
Washington, D.C.; About Narrator: No info provided.; Collection:U004 BASEMENT Room 024: Southwest Oral Histor ; Notes:Senator Ben Nighthorse Campbell is asked about the arts and censorship/ responsibility issues, along with financial obligations from the government and his responses to them. Argues against Dana Rohrabacher who wanted to cut NEA funding entirely. Campbell is presented as an expert for his role as politician and active artist. The previous segment on the tape interviews Andrea Martin. ;

