Washington, D.C.; About Narrator: No info provided.; Collection:U004 BASEMENT Room 024: Southwest Oral History ; Notes:Live call-in interviews with Rep. Donald Payne and Ben N. Campbell. Callers made statements on political correctness for the FDR memorial, Indian gambling, smoking, government shutdown, and hiring of the mentally ill.;

Commercial treaties--1993
Legislators--United States--1993
Washington, D.C.; About Narrator: No info provided.; Collection:U004 BASEMENT Room 024: Southwest Oral Histor ; Notes:Satellite feed interview in Senate recording studio with Senator Campbell and questions related to the North American Free Trade Agreement.;

Commercial treaties--1993
Legislators--United States--1993
Washington, D.C.; About Narrator: No info provided.; Collection:U004 BASEMENT Room 024: Southwest Oral Histor ; Notes:Questions and answers on the North American Free Trade Agreement. Campbell discusses maquiladoras on the border, how NAFTA creates exemptions and loopholes in environmental laws, the potential impact on the U.S. trucking industry, and airlines seeking to move their service shops across the border to save on labor costs. ;

Legislators--United States--1993
Television in politics--1993
Colorado--History; About Narrator: No info provided.; Collection:U004 BASEMENT Room 024: Southwest Oral Histor ; Notes:In Focus program interview by former Colorado U.S. Senator Hank Brown with Senator Campbell and U.S. Congressman Scott McInnis. McInnis talks about water issues, the federal deficit, CO's Taxpayer's Bill of Rights (TABOR) as a model for national policy, and the boycott of Colorado businesses over the passage of the anti-LGBT amendmend 2 in 1992. Campbell talks about federal balanced budget legislation, healthcare proposals under the Clinton adminstration(Campbell doesn't think the votes are there for a national healthcare bill), job growth, the wilderness bill (S.1029 and H.R. 762), and a bill to turn Black Canyon of the Gunnison National Monument into a National Park (H.R. 1321). ;

Harley-Davidson motorcycle--1997
Legislators--United States--1997
Washington, D.C.; About Narrator: No info provided.; Collection:U004 BASEMENT Room 024: Southwest Oral Histor ; Notes:Show Title: Amazing America; A Learning Channel programming that includes a history of the Harley-Davidson motorcycle with footage and interview of Senator Ben N. Campbell. There's an emphasis on the freedom of riding motorcycles, which Campbell compares to horseriding. There's also footage from the factory floor of motorcycles being assembled, and of Harley-Davidson enthusiasts making a pilgramage to the factory to see where their bikes "were born". Rep. Richard "Dick" Armey also appears briefly, also emphasizing the freedom of motorcycles as an American quality. ;

Indians of North America--Anecdotes--1997
Legislators--United States--1997
Washington, D.C.; About Narrator: No info provided.; Collection:U004 BASEMENT Room 024: Southwest Oral Histor ; Notes:Ben N. Campbell appears on an broadcast alongside celebrities Alex Trebek, Jerry Seinfield, and Valerie Bertinelli. Topics include the death of Chinese Premier Deng Xiaoping, the effect that death has on the reputation of public figures, cigar smoking culture, cynicism, and a lawsuit brought against a cast member of the Broadway musical Cats. (One of the duplicate VHS tapes is cataloged for the Delaney Library AV room.);

Indians of North America--Anecdotes--1995
Legislators--United States--1995
Washington, D.C.; About Narrator: No info provided.; Collection:U004 BASEMENT Room 024: Southwest Oral Histor ; Notes:Restless Warrior segment: includes a look into the life of Senator Campbell's daily life in the Senate. The segment puts a spotlight on how differently Campbell approaches the job of Senator, from his long hair and western fashion sense to his approach and outlook towards the work of legislating. His preference for Western Colorado over Washington D.C. gets special attention. Campbell also cites the change in name from Custer Battlefield to Little Bighorn Battlefield as on his best accomplishments. Fred Brown from the Denver Post, and Sherrie Wolff his former campaign manager are also interviewed.;

